{
  "$schema": "https://aka.ms/codetour-schema",
  "title": "00 — Orientation: the whole project in 5 minutes",
  "description": "Start here. This tour walks the project layout — main.go, migrations, each internal package, and the web and CLI gateways — before you dive into the detailed concept tours. It covers the no-args launcher, the 10-migration schema history, and every internal package including the new ones: turn, nodes, export, ext, ui/feature, and launch.",
  "steps": [
    {
      "file": "main.go",
      "line": 40,
      "title": "0.1 — What Balaur is",
      "description": "Balaur compiles to **one binary**. Run it bare (`balaur`) for the desktop-launcher experience, or with `balaur serve` for the traditional server path. Build with `CGO_ENABLED=0 go build -o balaur .` (release). The binary:\n\n- Embeds **PocketBase** as a Go library — a SQLite-backed data/auth engine\n- Serves the **Hearthwood Datastar web UI** from memory (no external server needed)\n- Runs **local LLM inference in-process** via the embedded **Kronk** SDK (`internal/kronk`) — GGUF models via llama.cpp through yzma, CGO-free, native lib dlopen'd at runtime\n- Supports an **opt-in, consent-gated OpenAI-compatible remote client** (`internal/llm/openai.go`) the owner can add from the Models page — never the default, never auto-selected\n\nThe binary does not contain models — those are downloaded data files. All application code, components, and CSS are embedded at compile time.\n\nSee `go.mod` for the dependency tree. Notice there is no web framework, no ORM, no router library — PocketBase provides the HTTP router; Go's standard library covers the rest."
    },
    {
      "file": "main.go",
      "line": 47,
      "title": "0.2 — The no-args launcher",
      "description": "```go\nif launch.IsLauncherInvocation(os.Args[1:]) {\n    _ = launch.IsFirstRun(launch.DataDir())\n    port, err := launch.SelectPort()\n    addr := fmt.Sprintf(\"127.0.0.1:%d\", port)\n    os.Args = append(os.Args[:1], \"serve\", \"--http\", addr, \"--dir\", launch.DataDir())\n    go launch.OpenAfterReady(addr)\n}\n```\n\nA bare `balaur` with no subcommand is the no-terminal entry point for desktop/GUI launchers. It works purely by **rewriting argv** into a normal `serve …` invocation _before_ `pocketbase.New()` — because `--dir` is an eager flag parsed at construction, the rewrite must happen first. Every existing path (explicit `serve`, CLI verbs, Makefile binds) is untouched.\n\n`internal/launch` provides the helpers: `IsLauncherInvocation`, `IsFirstRun`, `SelectPort` (tries the stable default 8099, falls back to any free loopback port), and `OpenAfterReady` (polls until the TCP listener accepts, then opens the system browser).\n\n**Tour 19** covers `internal/launch` and the bootstrapping sequence in depth."
    },
    {
      "file": "main.go",
      "line": 75,
      "title": "0.3 — main.go: thin wiring",
      "description": "```go\napp := pocketbase.New()\nmigratecmd.MustRegister(app, app.RootCmd, ...)\ncli.Register(app, app.RootCmd)        // machine-facing JSON gateway\napp.OnServe().BindFunc(func(se *core.ServeEvent) error {\n    registerKronkEngine(se.App)        // load in-process inference engine\n    web.Register(se)                   // Hearthwood Datastar gateway\n    registerRecap(se.App)              // hourly summary cron\n    registerNudge(se.App)              // minute nudge cron\n    registerBriefing(se.App)           // daily briefing cron\n    registerSearchIndex(se.App)        // FTS5 sidecar boot\n    knowledge.RegisterCacheInvalidation(se.App)\n    ...\n})\napp.OnTerminate().BindFunc(...) // unloads Kronk + closes search index\napp.Start()\n```\n\n`main.go` is intentionally thin — **orchestration only**. Four concerns:\n\n1. **Create the app** — PocketBase with default SQLite storage\n2. **Register migrations** — the blank import `_ \"balaur/migrations\"` runs `init()` in that package, registering the schema\n3. **Register gateways** — `cli.Register` (JSON) and `web.Register` (Datastar) both call `internal/turn` internally; they only render its events differently\n4. **Wire background jobs** — Kronk engine first, then recap, nudge, briefing, search index, and graph-link hooks all registered after serve is established\n\nEverything else lives in focused packages under `internal/`. AGENTS.md rule: *gateways adapt; they never re-implement.*"
    },
    {
      "file": "migrations/1749600000_init.go",
      "line": 15,
      "title": "0.4 — Schema as code: 10 migrations",
      "description": "```go\nfunc init() {\n    m.Register(InitCollections, dropCollections)\n}\n```\n\n`init()` runs automatically when the package is imported — before `main()`. It registers the migration with PocketBase's runner.\n\nThe filename prefix `1749600000` is a Unix timestamp — migrations run in filename order, so the timestamp ensures correct sequence. There are currently **10 migration files** (plus 3 test files) in the repo:\n\n1. `1749600000_init.go` — the consolidated baseline (plan 156): one `InitCollections` that creates the whole schema — `heads`, `conversations`, `messages`, `nodes`, `edges`, `audit_log`, `summaries`, `tasks`, `entries`, `extensions`, and the LLM config collections (`llm_providers`, `llm_models`, `llm_settings`, `owner_settings`)\n2. `1750000000_node_types.go` — adds the `node_types` registry, seeds the eight built-in types, and reopens `nodes.type` from a closed select to an open text field\n3. `1750000010_node_type_schemas.go` — adds `properties` + `template` fields to `node_types` and backfills the built-in type schemas\n4. `1750000020_tasks_to_nodes.go` — folds the `tasks` collection into the nodes spine as `type=task`\n5. `1750000030_measures_to_nodes.go` — folds measure entries into the nodes spine as `type=measure`\n6. `1750000040_day_type.go` — registers the `day` node type and backfills `on_day` edges\n7. `1750000050_unify_journal_into_day.go` — collapses `type=journal` nodes into `type=day` nodes\n8. `1750000060_node_type_icons.go` — icon field on node types\n9. `1750000070_conversation_compaction.go` — compaction support on conversations\n10. `1750000080_drop_memory_category.go` — removes the unused memory category axis\n\nAll collections have owner-only API rules. **Tour 19** covers migrations and schema evolution.\n\n**Explore the schema:** open `pb_data/data.db` in any SQLite viewer after running the server once, and browse the `_collections` table."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/turn/turn.go",
      "line": 69,
      "title": "0.5 — Package map: internal/turn (the shared pipeline)",
      "description": "```go\nfunc Run(ctx context.Context, app core.App, client llm.Client, userText string, emit func(agent.Event)) (Result, error)\n```\n\n`internal/turn` is the **one place** where a user turn becomes an agent response. Both gateways (`internal/web` and `internal/cli`) call `turn.Run` and only render its `agent.Event` stream in their own medium.\n\nThe pipeline assembles: context (conversation history, active head persona, relevant memories, tool list), then calls `agent.Loop.Run`, then persists the resulting messages and audit entries.\n\nAGENTS.md invariant: *gateways adapt; they never re-implement.* `turn` is the enforcer of that rule — behavior lives here, rendering is the gateway's job.\n\n**Tour 05** covers the turn pipeline in depth."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/llm/llm.go",
      "line": 44,
      "title": "0.6 — Package map: internal/llm & internal/kronk",
      "description": "```go\ntype Client interface {\n    ChatStream(ctx context.Context, msgs []Message, tools []ToolSpec) (<-chan Chunk, error)\n    Embed(ctx context.Context, texts []string) ([][]float32, error)\n}\n```\n\nBalaur's single seam to language models. `llm.Client` is the interface everything above it talks to — the agent loop, the turn pipeline, the embed helper.\n\n- `llm.go` — the `Client` interface and shared types (`Message`, `Chunk`, `ToolCall`, `ToolSpec`)\n- `env.go` — the `Collect` helper that drains a streaming channel to a full reply string\n- `openai.go` — the opt-in OpenAI-compatible HTTP client; reaches any endpoint that speaks the OpenAI chat/completions API\n- `presets.go` — the curated EU-jurisdiction cloud-provider catalog (Mistral today; US providers do not belong here)\n\nThe default local provider lives in **`internal/kronk`**: it runs local GGUF models in-process via the embedded Kronk SDK (llama.cpp through yzma, CGO-free). The opt-in remote path is `OpenAIClient` in `internal/llm` — consent-gated, never auto-selected.\n\n**Tour 11** covers local inference and the Kronk engine in depth.\n**Tour 01** covers the llm package interfaces and types."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/agent/agent.go",
      "line": 84,
      "title": "0.7 — Package map: internal/agent",
      "description": "```go\nfunc (l *Loop) Run(ctx context.Context, history []llm.Message, emit func(Event)) ([]llm.Message, error)\n```\n\nThe conversation loop: `messages → model → tool calls → tool results → model …` until the model answers in plain text.\n\n- `agent.go` — `Loop` struct and `Run()`, the orchestrator\n- `agent_test.go` — tests that drive the loop with a scripted `fakeClient`, no real model needed\n\nThe loop has no knowledge of PocketBase, HTTP, or the UI. It takes a `llm.Client`, a list of `Tool`s, and an `emit func(Event)` callback — then drives the conversation. The caller (`internal/turn`) decides what to do with events.\n\nEvent kinds: `text`, `reasoning`, `tool_start`, `tool_result`, `done`, `error`.\n\n**Tour 03** covers the loop step by step.\n**Tour 05** covers how `internal/turn` wraps the loop."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/nodes/nodes.go",
      "line": 89,
      "title": "0.8 — Package map: internal/nodes (the unified object spine)",
      "description": "```go\nfunc Create(app core.App, typ, title, body, status string, props map[string]any) (*core.Record, error)\n```\n\n`internal/nodes` is the **unified object spine** — tasks, quests, measures, days, and knowledge nodes are all records in the same `nodes` PocketBase collection, differentiated by a `type` field.\n\nKey operations: `Create`, `Update`, `Get`, `Drop`, `Transition` (status FSM with `ValidTransitions`), `AddEdge`, `Backlinks`, `Outbound`, `Neighborhood`.\n\nWithin the package, `schema.go`, `relations.go`, and `links.go` define the type registry and edge types, `query.go` holds the listing helpers, and `day.go` handles the special `day` aggregate node.\n\nThis consolidation is why the earlier migrations (`1750000020_tasks_to_nodes`, `1750000030_measures_to_nodes`) exist — they migrated domain-specific tables into this unified spine.\n\n**Tour 14** covers the knowledge spine and graph in depth."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/export/export.go",
      "line": 109,
      "title": "0.9 — Package map: internal/export, internal/ext, internal/ui",
      "description": "`internal/export` — the **Markdown mirror**: exports every node to a Johnny Decimal folder tree of `.md` files, optionally committed to a git repo, optionally encrypted with scrypt + AES-256-GCM (CGO-free). `ExportMirror` is the top-level entry point.\n\n`internal/ext` — the **extension sandbox**: loads owner-approved JS files from `pb_extensions/` via goja, runs them with a deliberately tiny surface (`balaur.http` inside handlers only — no filesystem, no shell). `Sync` discovers and proposes extensions; `Approve` pins a sha256 and enables a file. The `extensions` collection is the consent ledger.\n\n`internal/ui` — the **Hearthwood component system**: typed `gomponents` atoms (buttons, cards, badges, tabs, dialogs, …) plus sub-packages `internal/ui/chat` (chat organisms) and `internal/ui/shell` (page shell + sidebar). `internal/feature/*cards` and `internal/feature/storybook` compose these atoms into domain cards and a live component catalog at `/storybook`.\n\n**Tour 15** covers sovereign export and encryption.\n**Tour 16** covers the extension sandbox.\n**Tour 18** covers the component system and storybook."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/web/web.go",
      "line": 1,
      "title": "0.10 — The two gateways and where to go next",
      "description": "`internal/web` is the **Hearthwood Datastar UI gateway** — one of two surfaces over `internal/turn`.\n\n- `web.go` — `Register()` mounts routes; `guardLocalUI` is the DNS-rebinding + CSRF defence\n- `chat.go` — `POST /ui/chat`: calls `turn.Run` and adapts events to Datastar SSE patches\n- `cards.go` — typed card registry (`GET /ui/cards/{type}`, `GET /ui/show/{type}`)\n- domain pages: `tasks.go`, `knowledge.go`, `life.go`, `recap.go`, `day.go`, `heads.go`, `profile.go`, `models.go`, `graph.go`\n\n`internal/cli` is the **machine-facing JSON gateway** — every command prints one JSON envelope on stdout. The commands registered in `cli.Register` are `chat`, `task`, `memory`, `skill`, `note`, `search`, `life`, `journal`, `day`, `recap`, `history`, `audit`, `verify`, `model`, `self`, `ext`, `export`, `doctor`, `seed`.\n\n**Where to go from here:**\n\n| Tour | Topic |\n|------|-------|\n| **03** | The agent loop (`internal/agent`) |\n| **05** | The turn pipeline (`internal/turn`, `heads`, `verify`) |\n| **07** | The web gateway (`internal/web`) |\n| **10** | The CLI API (`internal/cli`) |\n| **11** | Local inference: the Kronk engine |\n| **12** | Persistence & the store seam (`internal/conversation`, `store`) |\n| **13** | Companion domain: quests, life & recaps |\n| **14** | The knowledge spine: nodes & the graph |\n| **15** | Sovereign export & encryption |\n| **16** | The extension sandbox (`internal/ext`) |\n| **17** | The tool surface (`internal/tools`) |\n| **18** | The component system & storybook (`internal/ui`, `feature/*`) |\n| **19** | Bootstrapping (`main.go`, `internal/launch`, `seed`, `migrations`) |"
    }
  ]
}
